Analyzing HotelController + HotelServiceImpl for IDOR. 2.Endpoints: POST /hotel/add/{key}/{packageId}, DELETE /hotel/delete/{hotelId}/{key}, PUT /hotel/update/{key}. 3.Authorization flow: authKey parameter in URL → sessionRepository.findByAuthkey() → userType check for 'admin'. 4.IDOR check: Authorization happens before object access in service layer. 5.Hotel entity reveals schema with auto-generated Integer IDs (predictable). 6.Found multiple IDOR vulnerabilities: a)Predictable Integer IDs for hotels b)Authorization bypass possible via parameter manipulation c)Service layer authorization is insufficient. 7.Service implementation shows no owner/tenant checks on hotels. 8.Once authenticated as admin, can access any hotel record.",    "analysis": "After reviewing the complete code path from controller to service implementation, confirmed IDOR vulnerability exists. The code uses predictable integer IDs for hotels and lacks proper authorization boundaries. While there is basic role-based auth checking for 'admin', there are no tenant isolation or ownership checks on hotel records. An attacker who gains admin access can enumerate and access any hotel in the system due to sequential Integer IDs. The service layer only verifies admin role but doesn't validate if the admin should have access to specific hotel records. The @CrossOrigin(origins='*') annotation compounds the issue by allowing requests from any domain.",    "poc": "1. Obtain admin authKey via authentication 2. Enumerate hotel IDs sequentially: curl -X DELETE 'http://target/hotel/delete/1/admin_auth_key' curl -X DELETE 'http://target/hotel/delete/2/admin_auth_key' etc. 3. Modify any hotel: curl -X PUT 'http://target/hotel/update/admin_auth_key' -d '{\"hotelId\":1,\"hotelName\":\"Hacked\"}' 4. Add hotel to any package: curl -X POST 'http://target/hotel/add/admin_auth_key/1' -d '{\"hotelName\":\"Evil Hotel\"}'",    "confidence_score": 9,    "vulnerability_types": ["IDOR"],    "context_code": []}